'''Tsutomu Ujitani''' (宇治谷 孟, August 5, 1918<ref name="bukko">『現代物故者事典1991～1993』（日外アソシエーツ、1994th year ）p.99</ref> – November 5, 1992) was a Japanese historian and literary scholar. He is known for producing the first modern Japanese translation of the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>Ujitani (1988, Volume 1), cover.</ref> and also translated the {{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|12=draft|12=draft}} into modern Japanese.
== Overview == Tsutomu Ujitani was born in Kyoto Prefecture in 1918<ref name="syoku-nihongi-okuzuke">Ujitani (1995), colophon.</ref>. He graduated from the Department of Japanese Language and Literature at {{ill|Hosei University|ja|法政大学|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1941, the Faculty of Letters at {{ill|Waseda University|ja|早稲田大学|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1943, and the Faculty of Economics at {{ill|Ritsumeikan University|ja|立命館大学|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1952<ref name="syoku-nihongi-okuzuke" />. After teaching at several high schools, including {{ill|Seifu High School|ja|清風高校|12=draft|12=draft}}, he became a professor at {{ill|Shiga Bunkyo Junior College|ja|滋賀文教短期大学|12=draft|12=draft}} and a lecturer at {{ill|Nara College of Arts|ja|奈良芸術短期大学|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="syoku-nihongi-okuzuke" />.
During his time at Waseda University, he attended lectures by poet and literary scholar {{ill|Kuho Kubota|ja|窪田空穂|12=draft|12=draft}}. Kubota expressed his hope for someone to create accessible modern Japanese translations of the *Nihon Shoki* and *Shoku Nihongi* to help the public better understand Japanese history. This inspired Ujitani to undertake the task himself years later, as such translations had not yet been produced<ref name="syoku-nihongi-atogaki">Ujitani (1995), 11. 480–483.</ref>.
On November 5, 1992, Ujitani died in a traffic accident<ref name="syoku-nihongi-atogaki" />. The manuscript for his *Shoku Nihongi (Volume 3): Complete Modern Japanese Translation* was completed posthumously with the help of his wife, Teruchiyo, and his brother, Yoshio Ujitani, a professor at {{ill|Aichi Gakusen University|ja|愛知学泉大学|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="syoku-nihongi-atogaki" />.
== Works == * *Nihon Shoki: Complete Modern Japanese Translation* (全訳 現代文 日本書紀), Sōgei Publishing, 1986 (2 volumes) * *Nihon Shoki: Complete Modern Japanese Translation* (全現代語訳 日本書紀), Kodansha Gakujutsu Bunko, 1988 (2 volumes) ''' ISBN 4-06-158833-8, ISBN 4-06-158834-6 * *Shoku Nihongi: Complete Modern Japanese Translation* (全現代語訳 続日本紀), Kodansha Gakujutsu Bunko, 1992–1995 (3 volumes) ''' ISBN 4-06-159030-8, ISBN 4-06-159031-6, ISBN 4-06-159032-4 * *Wanshan Yue* (晩香玉), Bungeisha, 2000. ISBN 4-8355-0067-9 – A romance novel.
== References == {{Reflist}} == See Also == * {{ill|Rikkokushi|ja|六国史|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Tei Morita|ja|森田悌|12=draft|12=draft}} – Historian and professor emeritus at {{ill|Gunma University|ja|群馬大学|12=draft|12=draft}}, who translated later historical texts, such as {{ill|Nihon Kōki|ja|日本後紀|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shoku Nihon Kōki|ja|続日本後紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, into modern Japanese.
{{Normdaten}}
